article.description: Erin Buescher scored 16 points and Yolanda Griffith had 15 points and eight rebounds to lead the Monarchs to a 75-69 victory over the Silver Stars.
article.headline: Buescher, Griffith lift slumping Monarchs past Silver Stars
article.linkText: Buescher, Griffith lift Monarchs past Silver Stars
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Despite missing her first six shots and going scoreless in the first 36 minutes, Kara Lawson came through in the end.

Lawson had six points in the final 3:52 to help the Sacramento Monarchs beat San Antonio 75-69 on Wednesday night, handing the Silver Stars their first road loss of the season.

Erin Buescher scored 16 points, Yolanda Griffith had 15 points and eight rebounds and Nicole Powell added 10 points for Sacramento (6-5). However, the biggest contribution came late from Lawson, who made two key jumpers and a pair of free throws.

"I like taking the big shot, I always have since I was a little kid," Lawson said. "We ran some pick-and-rolls and I was playing off them."

Lawson connected on a medium-range jumper to put the Monarchs ahead for good, 65-63 with 3:52 left. She made another jumper to increase Sacramento's lead to 71-65 and later added two free throws.

"That was a hard win, that's a much improved San Antonio team then the ones we remember the last few years," Sacramento coach John Whisenant said. "To win tough games you have to do it at the defensive end. We did that."

Sophia Young scored 16 points for San Antonio (6-5). Kendra Wecker and LaToya Thomas both had 12, Vickie Johnson added 11 and Shanna Zolman 10.

After a productive first half, the Sacramento defense pressured San Antonio into mistakes and poor shooting in the second half when the Silver Stars scored 29 points.

"They do a great job of forcing you to create offense without any rhythm," Hughes said.

Buescher shot 6-for-7 from the field and hit all four free throws in producing another big game off the bench.

"Erin's play off the bench made a tremendous impact for them," Hughes said. "She is quicker and more active this year. We talked about her before the game, but we still didn't do a good job on her."

The Monarchs led 57-54 after three quarters and scored the first four points of the fourth to increase the lead to 61-54.

San Antonio responded with seven straight points, the final two on a putback by Young to tie the game 61-61 with 6:06 remaining.

Despite a late 12-2 run by the Monarchs, the Silver Stars led 40-38 at the half.
